E=mc^2
======

https://thecuriousastronomer.wordpress.com/2017/10/03/derivation-of-latex-emc2/
dE = Fdx et F=dp/dt (p moment), donne dE=v dp
or p=mv où m=m_0/\sqrt{1-v^2/c^2}
donc dp=v dm + m dv et on calcule dm/dv=mv/(c^2-m^2), donc dE=c^2m
donc E-E0=c^2 \int_m0^m dm = c^2(m-m0) d'où E0=m0c^2 et E=mc^2.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass%E2%80%93energy_equivalence
https://arxiv.org/pdf/physics/0308039.pdf A simple derivation of E = mc 
References: https://physics.stackexchange.com/questions/363/getting-started-self-studying-general-relativity

Mécanique relativiste
=====================

Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_transformation
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy%E2%80%93momentum_relation
 E^2 = (pc)^2 + (m0 c^2)^2 = mc^2
 Autrement dit, si pp est le four momentum (E/c, mv)=(E/c, \gamma m_0 v),
 on a pp^2=-m0^2 c^2
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-momentum
 On a xx=(ct, x), donc vv=dxx/dt=\gamma (c, v), pp=m_0 vv=(E/c, mv)

  Lorentz boost (x direction)
      t ′ = γ (t−vx/c^2), x′=γ(x−vt), y′=y, z′=z
  where v is the relative velocity between frames in the x-direction, c is the speed of light, and γ = 1/\sqrt{1−v^2/c^2}

https://www.quora.com/Is-there-a-relativistic-equivalent-of-each-of-Newtons-3-laws
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relativistic_Lagrangian_mechanics

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geodesics_in_general_relativity
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stress%E2%80%93energy_tensor
